By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. show awareness of the nature of English listening and speaking;
2. identify, express and justify appropriate learning objectives for the teaching of listening and speaking, including pronunciation;
3. plan activities and procedures to support their expressed objectives;
4. express a rationale for choices made during lesson planning; and

5. carry out a teaching plan in front of peers

6. reflect upon their lessons and identify areas of strength and areas for improvement.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. understand the theories and concepts that underlie the processes of reading and writing;
2. use a variety of approaches to teach reading and writing to learners of different proficiency levels;
3. teach reading and writing as inter-related skills and in integration with other language skills; and

4. interweave the teaching and assessment of reading and writing so that they can plan, teach and assess reading and writing effectively.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. grasp the major principles underpinning language testing and assessment;
2. explain the different purposes of language assessment and understand how assessment for learning and assessment as learning can be used to promote learning and improve teaching;
3. acquire relevant techniques to construct language tests that focus on grammar, vocabulary, speaking, listening, reading and writing;
4. evaluate and critique language tests used in local schools by applying the assessment principles learnt from the course;
5. enhance their assessment literacy for effective English language teaching.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:
1. show awareness of different research designs, and reasons for choosing between them;
2. identify the steps needed to carry out a piece of classroom-based research;
3. express a research focus and develop research questions;
4. justify choice of data collection methods;
5. evaluate data collection and analysis;
6. write up a proposal for classroom-based research; and
7. demonstrate academic literacy (including academic honesty).

By the end of the course, students will have:
1. acquired the experience of conducting a classroom-based study in a real classroom setting on a topic of their choice;
2. acquired the experience of writing up a report for a classroom-based study;
3. acquired the experience of presenting their proposals to an academic audience;
4. become familiar with the steps taken to conduct a classroom-based study;
5. developed skills in data analysis and data presentation;
6. been able to draw conclusions and implications from the findings of their own classroom-based study;
7. gained a better understanding of the area of their study;
8. sharpened academic writing skills;
9. developed a foundation for further research in terms of understanding of the research process; and
10. developed positive attitudes towards professional development via conducting classroom-based research

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. have a better theoretical understanding of the relationship between language teaching approaches, syllabus design and materials development, and recognize how the different models of language teaching would result in differences for instructional methods, syllabus design and materials development;
2. formulate materials design principles that suit their future teaching context;
3. evaluate materials in use e.g. text books, authentic materials, multimedia materials….etc in their future teaching contexts, and select from, adapt or supplement these materials to make ELT classroom learning experience more interesting; and

4. design authentic and communicative language task for the use of authentic materials in ELT classrooms.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. have a perspective of CALL with regard to the 'history' of IT and the learning theories that underlie different approaches to the use of IT in English language teaching;
2. develop a framework for understanding CALL materials and for putting them into perspective;
3. be able to critically analyse CALL programs and materials; and

4. evaluate the value of IT as a teaching tool – in terms of what can and cannot be reasonably achieved in developing students' English language skills.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. increase awareness of the theories and issues relating to the English language curriculum;
2. develop informed and critical approaches to recent and current developments in this area;
3. plan and implement effective improvements to overall ELT curriculum design, use of instructional materials, assessment and teaching;
4. offer informed knowledge and understanding of teaching activities with reference to the ELT curriculum; and

5. evaluate the effectiveness of ELT curriculum.

By the end of the course, students will:

1. be able to demonstrate an understanding of the place of language arts in language education, focusing on the Experience Strand of the English Language curriculum;
2. become familiar with language-based approaches to literature to enhance awareness of the properties of language use in literary materials in the light of communicative language resources;
3. be able to demonstrate skills in language arts materials selection, textual analysis and task design for integration into language teaching curricular; and

4. have fostered interest in reading different language arts genres for pleasure and for language enrichment.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. understand the principles that underlie English enrichment activities;
2. plan and organize language enrichment activities to enhance students' language learning experience;
3. conduct and evaluate language enrichment activities effectively; and

4. integrate language enrichment activities into the formal and informal curricula.
